# SOLID · KISS · DRY Engineering Principles

Apply these principles to every file, component, function, and module. They are non-negotiable quality gates, not suggestions.

---

## SOLID

### S — Single Responsibility Principle
Every module, class, component, or function must have **one reason to change**.

- A React component either fetches data **or** renders UI — never both. Use a custom hook for data logic, a component for presentation.
- A utility function does one thing. If the name contains "and", split it.
- A Supabase Edge Function handles one operation. Separate auth, business logic, and DB access into distinct layers.
- Keep files under ~200 lines. If a file grows beyond that, it is doing too much.

```ts
// ❌ Wrong — component owns too many concerns
export function UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  useEffect(() => { supabase.from('users').select().eq('id', userId).then(...) }, []);
  const handleUpdate = async (data) => { await supabase.from('users').update(data)... };
  return <form onSubmit={handleUpdate}>...</form>;
}

// ✅ Correct — concerns separated
// hooks/useUser.ts — data logic
export function useUser(userId: string) {
  return useQuery({ queryKey: ['user', userId], queryFn: () => fetchUser(userId) });
}

// components/UserProfile.tsx — pure presentation + interaction
export function UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const { data: user } = useUser(userId);
  return <UserForm user={user} onSubmit={updateUser} />;
}
```

---

### O — Open/Closed Principle
Code should be **open for extension, closed for modification**.

- Extend behaviour through composition and props, not by editing existing components.
- Use variant maps, strategy patterns, or plugin-style config objects instead of growing if/else chains.
- Never add a new feature by forking a component. Parameterise it instead.

```ts
// ❌ Wrong — must modify function to add new alert types
function showAlert(type: string, message: string) {
  if (type === 'success') { ... }
  else if (type === 'error') { ... }
  // Every new type = modifying this file
}

// ✅ Correct — extend by adding to the map, never touching the function
const ALERT_CONFIG = {
  success: { icon: CheckIcon, class: 'bg-green-100' },
  error:   { icon: XIcon,     class: 'bg-red-100'   },
  info:    { icon: InfoIcon,  class: 'bg-blue-100'  },
} satisfies Record<string, AlertConfig>;

function Alert({ type, message }: AlertProps) {
  const config = ALERT_CONFIG[type];
  return <div className={config.class}><config.icon />{message}</div>;
}
```

